ational development assistance partnerships for education development and reform.&amp;nbsp;It argues that we must give greater recognition to the development and reconciliation of such scalar and temporal tensions.&amp;nbsp;The Eastern Caribbean is illustrative of many small states that ? because of their multiple socio-political, economic, and geographical scales ? are forced to balance and negotiate diverse understandings and uses of scale and time in a world that exhibits an increasingly escalated and intensified globalisation. Accordingly, the study focuses on partnerships among Eastern Caribbean Ministries of Education and four donor agencies (Canadian International Development Agency, Department for International Development, European Union, World Bank/Caribbean Development Bank) between 1990 and 2005.&amp;nbsp;The analytical framework utilises two bodies of theoretical literature: Boaventura de Sousa Santos?s critical post-structuralism and Caribbean knowledges.&amp;nbsp;The methodological tenets are derived largely from a research orientation that emphasises the importance of multidisciplinary qualitative approaches in comparative and international education research.&amp;nbsp;Using an interpretivist strategy, the summative analysis argues for the recognition and closer examination of the impact of differing conceptions and uses of scale and time as mechanisms of power and control in international development assistance partnerships.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-07-06</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>23703</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impac